---
import BlogPost from '../../../../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
import { BLOG_POSTS } from '../../../../data/blog';

const meta = BLOG_POSTS.find((p) => p.slug === 'brrrr-refinance-dscr')!;

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'What is BRRRR?',
    answer:
      'BRRRR stands for Buy, Rehab, Rent, Refinance, Repeat. It is a real-estate-investor strategy of acquiring distressed property in cash or with short-term financing, renovating it, leasing it to tenants, and then refinancing with a long-term loan (often DSCR) to extract equity for the next purchase.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How long do I have to wait before I can refinance after a BRRRR purchase?',
    answer:
      'Most DSCR lenders require 3 to 6 months of seasoning on a cash-out refinance after purchase. Some lenders allow shorter seasoning with delayed-financing rules if the original purchase was all-cash and within 6 months. Clout publishes specific seasoning rules per program inside TPO Connect — confirm before locking the refi timeline.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can I refinance the rehab cost into the new DSCR loan?',
    answer:
      'Yes, within the LTV cap. The DSCR refi is sized against the post-rehab appraised value, not the original purchase price. If you bought at $200K, put $40K of rehab in, and the appraisal comes back at $320K, a 75% LTV cash-out refi sizes at $240K — covering your purchase, rehab, and pulling additional equity for the next deal.',
  },
];
---

<BlogPost
  slug={meta.slug}
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  category={meta.category}
  datePublished={meta.datePublished}
  dateModified={meta.dateModified}
  lead="The refi leg of BRRRR is where most investors switch to DSCR — because their tax returns can't qualify them for what the rehabbed property actually cash-flows. Knowing the LTV ladder, the seasoning rules, and how to size the refi before the rehab is done is the difference between recycling capital in 90 days and getting stuck."
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <h2>Why BRRRR investors switch to DSCR for the refi</h2>
  <p>
    The Buy, Rehab, Rent, Refinance, Repeat cycle runs on capital velocity. The faster equity
    rotates out of one property and into the next, the faster the portfolio compounds. The
    bottleneck most BRRRR investors hit is at the "R" — refinancing. A conventional cash-out
    refi requires two years of tax returns, an acceptable DTI, and a property count under 10.
    DSCR refis require none of those. The property's post-rehab cash flow qualifies the loan;
    your W-2 and Schedule E are irrelevant.
  </p>

  <h2>The LTV ladder for DSCR cash-out refis</h2>
  <p>
    DSCR cash-out refis cap lower than purchases — typically 70–75% LTV depending on FICO,
    DSCR ratio, and property type. The arithmetic that decides BRRRR profitability:
  </p>
  <div class="key-stats">
    <div><span class="k">Strong FICO + DSCR 1.25+</span><span class="v">Up to 75% LTV</span></div>
    <div><span class="k">Standard band</span><span class="v">70% LTV</span></div>
    <div><span class="k">Lower FICO / DSCR &lt;1.10</span><span class="v">65% LTV</span></div>
  </div>

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>
    Acquired a $200K duplex for cash. Put $40K of rehab in. Six months later, the property is
    leased at $1,500 per unit ($3,000 total) and appraises at $320K. Post-rehab PITIA at 7.5%
    on a refi is roughly $1,950, so DSCR ratio = $3,000 ÷ $1,950 = 1.54 — strong. At 75% LTV
    on the $320K appraisal, the cash-out refi sizes at $240K. That recovers the $200K
    purchase, the $40K rehab, and recycles capital into the next BRRRR.
  </p>

  <h2>Seasoning rules — the 3-to-6-month wait</h2>
  <p>
    Most DSCR lenders require the borrower to season the property for 3 to 6 months before a
    cash-out refi. Seasoning starts at the recording date of the original purchase deed.
    Delayed-financing exceptions exist on some programs when the original purchase was all-cash
    and within 6 months — the cash-out refi is treated more like a rate-and-term, sized against
    cost rather than appraised value. Confirm seasoning specifics with the AE before you lock
    a rehab timeline around the refi date.
  </p>

  <h2>How to size the refi before the rehab is done</h2>
  <p>
    The mistake BRRRR investors make is starting the rehab without knowing the post-rehab
    appraisal target. The fix:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Pull rent comps</strong> for the as-rehabbed unit before purchase. Most useful: the same submarket, same unit count, same bedroom count, completed within the last 6 months.</li>
    <li><strong>Pull sale comps</strong> for fully-rehabbed comparable properties. The post-rehab appraisal will look like these.</li>
    <li><strong>Back-solve LTV cap × appraisal target = max refi.</strong> Then subtract purchase + rehab + closing costs. The remainder is the equity you recycle.</li>
    <li><strong>If the equity recycle is below what you need, do not start the rehab.</strong> The property won't BRRRR — it will trap capital.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="callout">
    <p class="callout-title">Pre-rehab DSCR check</p>
    <p>
      Estimated post-rehab market rent × 12 ÷ projected post-rehab PITIA ≥ 1.10 → file
      qualifies for standard pricing. If it lands below 1.10, plan for tighter pricing or
      smaller cash-out. Run this in the scenario desk before closing on the acquisition.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Frequently asked</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    {faqs.map((f) => (
      <details>
        <summary>{f.question}</summary>
        <div><p>{f.answer}</p></div>
      </details>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Next steps</h2>
  <p>
    Run your BRRRR refi scenario through the <a href="/tpo-connect/">Clout scenario desk</a>
    before you start the rehab — getting the LTV math wrong is the most expensive part of
    the cycle. See also:
    <a href="/resources/blog/dscr-loans-real-estate-investors/">DSCR Loans for Real Estate Investors</a> ·
    <a href="/resources/blog/cash-reserves-dscr-loan/">Cash Reserves for DSCR Loans</a> ·
    <a href="/resources/glossary/#brrrr">BRRRR</a> in the glossary.
  </p>
</BlogPost>
